WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.400
Hey everybody, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:16.860
We're part of the Posit support team and today we're going to walk through testing Postgres

00:00:16.860 --> 00:00:20.080
database connections from the command line.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:29.820
So both Posit Workbench, Connect and also Package Manager use an SQLite3 database by

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:34.740
default which is just a file, a text file based database.

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:39.200
And at some point you may want to move to Postgres and before you do that a good idea

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:45.540
is to check that your Linux terminal can connect to your Postgres host before you try connecting

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:46.860
the product.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:54.180
So a good utility that you can use is the pg underscore is ready command.

00:00:54.180 --> 00:01:04.120
So I have a pre-made example here but effectively you put in your Postgres database details.

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:09.279
So using pg underscore is ready the database in this case is Posit.

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:12.379
The host name is called Postgres host.

00:01:12.379 --> 00:01:16.459
The port is 5432 and the user is Postgres.

00:01:16.459 --> 00:01:21.500
If we hit enter there we'll see that our database is accepting connections.

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:27.379
And in most cases that should be enough to then go into your product configuration file

00:01:27.379 --> 00:01:33.419
and start migrating your data from SQLite3 to Postgres.

00:01:33.419 --> 00:01:38.540
But something else you can do is to validate that you have permissions into the specific

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:43.459
database itself is you can run a psql command.

00:01:43.459 --> 00:01:49.980
So this is a Postgres command which specifies largely the same details.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:56.300
So you specify your user here which is Postgres port 5432.

00:01:56.300 --> 00:02:01.459
The host is still Postgres host and the database is Posit.

00:02:01.459 --> 00:02:06.180
And you'll see that we're connected to Postgres and we can view the schema that way.

